Also, these edX universities usually require TOEFL, Gre and all sorts of English tests.. But I think Unicaf will only request for your WAEC English and maybe any English electives you did in undergrad.
We do this in my own company

Edx don't all require GRE though.. Like I said the major difference between both is that with Edx universities, the institutions are whom you'll directly interface with. Lessons from them. Study materials from them etc.. With unicaf, the partner institution is really just a partner. They'll share their syllabus, but unicaf handles the lessons, learning materials etc.. The Partner uni just gives you a certificate after everything.
Difference will be in the quality of the Learning.. But if certificate is your major interest, then unicaf is aite.

First thing is to understand is which area of DE are you looking into? Streaming or Data warehousing?
Which would you recommend for a newbie?
I meant someone who's just looking at transitioning into DE

For streaming. You have to focus more on the kinesis family, SQS, SNS, Lambda, VPC, S3 , and Cloud watch... You will have to find resources that treat each of them thoroughly, especially those that use Python Boto3 to interact with the services.. For Data warehousing and Data lake, your focus will be on. Redshift, Athena, S3 and maybe glue.. No matter which one you choose, you will also learn how to deploy them with Terraform, dockerize some of the services, write python, SQL and Spark.. No book really joins these pieces together. You have to merge things here and there. If your focus is streaming - though I hardly see 9ja DEs work on projects in this area - I can help point to some resources.
Which one u wan focus?
You may please shed more light on which aspect you think someone who's just starting off should look into
What's the difference between the two?
I have some exposure to Terraform & Docker already 🤔

It is tricky. What you will end up doing depends on the company you later find yourself.. If I want to advise someone looking into the Nigeria market, I will say data lake/warehousing and migration path.. Redshift, Athena, glue , dbt, Airflow. If you have any Open Source ETL tool then you can ignore glue.
How about someone looking at global opportunities?
Streaming?
Streaming has to do with real-time data (usually in kb per millisecs) while Data warehousing and stuff deal with batch data.

Name: Opeyemi Fabiyi
Content: Boss 🙌🙌🙌

Either way can work.... But this has worked many times.. Use latent dirichlet allocation model. Test whether the distribution per activity description of hidden semantic information could predict the classes (charity or humanitarian etc). Since the data is about <10^5; Train LDA Model on about 75% of the activity description (randomized sample).. Grab Topic distributions for every activity description using the LDA Model. Use Topic Distributions directly as feature vectors in supervised classification models (random forest preferably) and get F1-score.. Use the same LDA model(same hyperparameters) to get topic distributions for other 30% (unseen data). Run supervised classification models again on the 30% vectors and see if this generalizes.. If the supervised F1-scores on the unseen data generalizes, then you can posit that the 70% topic model has identified latent semantic structure that persists over time in this activity description.. NB

The possible output is all about the concept of left join.. Left table - Loan. Right Table - Users. All columns on the left table(Loan) will be returned regardless of whether a row from the left table has a matching row from the right table(User).. If there is no match, the columns from the right table(Users) will contain NULL.. Also for the where clause, it will filter it by the due date when is >= “2018-01-01” and then ordered it in descending order I.e the least date will be 2018-01-01.. ID - It's gonna return all rows. Amount due - It's going to retuned all rows. Due date - It's going to return all rows.. First name - This column might contain NULL. Last  name - This column might contain NULL. In summary, if the loan id has no users, the values in the first name and last name are NULL.

Name: Chinwe O
Content: @2347086742097 thanks for the response. Really detailed !
Actually @2347086742097 has done major justice to the question actually but If I would add anything, it would be the following

*Data Lake* - This is pretty much or most times an object or cloud storage you use to house data in its raw format. From Structured to semi-structured and unstructured data. The good thing about it is that it accepts data in all format but the downside to it most times is that you don't get the simple advantages you get with a Data Warehouse like querying your data, having ACID BASE transactions and operations with data.. You have to implement data governance and policies yourself so your data lake doesn't become a *DATA SWAMP* .. But these days there are a bunch of technologies out there that helps put in all of these things in place and help implement a good functioning data lake properly. examples are LakeFS which is bring git versioning to Data Environments, some refer to it as the perfect data management tools. Another tool is Delta Lake which is used to upgrade the data lake by making it possible for you to perform ACID BASE transactions on data artefacts in your data lake because you are able to save your structured data as Delta Tables that you can write SQL queries against and also delta lake brings it data governance and management to your data lake because it does versioning out of the box, meta data handling and also keeps the logs of your data artefacts at different point so you are able to perform time travel operations on your data assets. Some other the cool advantages of this is you are able to store your data for long with less cost and you are also able to separate your storage layer from your computing layer in your data environment or infrastructure.

*Data Warehouse* - I would keep it short here as this is the defacto run to environment for structured data on a wide scale, And there are a bunch of technologies out there that handles this and implements this in different strategies, so it is up to you to sit it out with Data Engineers and other Data Experts to figure out what suits your use case best.. With this , Business teams are able to perform analytics on a wide scale... The major downside to Data Warehouses is the fact that you cannot handle unstructured data and also it takes some special kind of skill and implementations to handle semi-structured data.
But it would be unfair to talk about those two without talking about the LakeHouse and Data Mesh.

So remember for the data lake, remember I said that there are technologies people used to handle it flaws.. So in actual sense ehn,. A LakeHouse is actually *Data Lake + Data Warehouse*. *A lakehouse* builds upon the strength and flaws of these two technologies and concepts.. So Ideally when you use Delta Lake to handle the flaws of a typical data lake, you are actually implementing a Lakehouse.. The easiest way to implement the LakeHouse is by using *Databricks* environment out of the box with any of your cloud or object storage or any file system of your choice be it Hadoop FS, LakeFS or even minIO storage
This message was deleted
This message was deleted

Though you can also have the Open Source implementation of the Lakehouse by setting up your environment and infrastructure yourself by using Open source tools and environment by following the following steps.. Remember that the Lakehouse and data lake can handle both batch streaming data.. - Have a cloud or object storage of your choice or any file system that support delta lake. - Spark Environment with Delta Lake Packages and jar configured and installed(So you have access to all of Databricks Delta Lake Capabilities). - So you can code in Pyspark via a jupyter notebook, scalar or any programming language of your choice using the Delta Lake Spark API for the language you prefer.. - LakeFS to bring in git versioning and Data Management to your big data or normal data environment. - Airflow for Workflow Orchestration and Scheduling. - And since it is a Lakehouse, it can speak to other technologies like *dbt* , *Airbyte* etc
Lastly - A *Data Mesh*

So you can see a data mesh as you designing an end to end data infrastructure or environment with the domain or business or industry concerned being at the center of your design.. So you design the environment to meet the past, future and present needs of that particular domain.. A real life example is this

It was a bank so it was purely on prem. The stagingdb was SQL server. How do you think this could have been structured better?

The architecture can still be reproduced on-prem. Spark integrates well with SQL server too.  Spark will be used on both the batch and speed layer. The idea is to make the speed layer process only the data needed by the by the business in near-real-time. A spark job will process the batch data at a later time when the business won't be impacted(probably midnight). The consolidated view of what is needed is what the dashboards will be displaying.
The only drawback is that you won't have a "true" view until the next spark job. The business will decide the level of latency that is not too serious .

This is about to be a little long read.. I think the biggest career turnover in the data space happens in data science, unfortunately. And by "data science" here, I'm specifically referring to the typical scope of work of a "data scientist", because sometimes the term "data science" can refer to one entire side of the coin of the data space itself, the other side being data management/governance.. Now, talking about turnover, I've seen that it can be hard to break into data science after the learning journey, even harder to succeed in the role, and hardest to sustain success and keep up the progression of career growth.. Most people give up at Stage 1. Stage 2 is where some others come to the objective realisation that data science isn't the best area for them to make impact with data. Stage 3 is where you see the rest of the pivot where people permanently ditch DS for other data areas such as DA or DE, or even completely outside such as product or engineering.. I've been opportune to function across DA, DS, DE, sometimes focusing on one individual area and other times doing a combination, but I've spent the shortest time doing data engineering and the longest doing data science. In my experience across the 3 areas, it's easy to understand why data science gets the most turnover. Data science is the most hyped amongst all the data specialisations. And, if you ask me the hype is well worth it – data science literally sits at the center of decision optimisation and automation for orgs that are creating and monetising data value streams.. The problem with this hype is that the complexities are not presented well enough or even at all, so it typically sounds like you only need to learn coding (Python/R), a little bit of statistics, and then machine learning. So you get excited and learn these, then realise that with only these skills, you are just about the most useless DS professional in the competitive talent pool. You even find that your counterparts have additional tools in their stack (e.g., badass SQL, Spark, Kafka, Storm, SageMaker, etc). Now, you have a new motivation, so you throw in more tools to your learning curve.. But all the while you have not learned or developed skills in the deep, intricate principles for driving business value with data science. You have not learned how to extend the capabilities of a data engineer and analyst to get additional business value that those areas alone cannot provide. Note the keyword

You nailed it! The ability to drive business value is what keeps one in demand. I was about to extend my earlier post by adding how data scientists can create business value using data science.

For example, in data science, the problems we solve typically revolve around causal inference, machine learning or decision optimisation. Some jobs might focus on only 1 or 2 of these areas. Now, applying any of these 3 scientific pillars to business problems presents us with 2 layers of difficulty.. One layer is the scientific layer, where the difficulties are mostly around reasoning and problem solving. Reasoning, because the problems (after being formalised in a data science framework) are not always open-ended and you have to draw out the connections and literally create the trajectory for how your solution should evolve. Reasoning requires abstract thought and the ability to deduce things from first principles, and this is one of the most important skills for data science yet the most untapped. Problem solving is another difficulty because you have to be adaptive enough to different solution approaches until you find the most suitable. Also requires you to be persistent enough to push through roadblocks, and alert and objective enough to spot limitations in your methodology and skillfully eliminate them.. Now, the second layer is the business layer, where the difficulty lies with aligning science to business. Science is mostly deterministic, business is mostly stochastic. Applying data science to business then means developing or implementing the specific principles of science that allow us to deal with the "stochastic" nature of a business landscape that is constantly "changing" with new "data". This is why data science is built on solid foundations of calculus, linear algebra, and probability. Notice the 3 things in quotes

Name: Opeyemi Fabiyi
Content: Tableau & Redash comparison will be difficult they kind of serve same purpose though different.. Tableau - Great aesthetics and all but uses memory because you have import the data into the BI and also do modeling in that same layer which is also similar to Power BI.. Redash on the hand is an SQL based viz tool but might be difficult to maintain too as the data scale if you don’t have a separate transformation/modeling layer

Name: Opeyemi Fabiyi
Content: To recommend what’s your current stack your BI layer will be consuming from?

Name: Opeyemi Fabiyi
Content: Oh, cool you are implementing MDS

Name: Opeyemi Fabiyi
Content: In that case since you are using dbt as your layer you can check out Metabase or Superset

Name: Opeyemi Fabiyi
Content: I think will fit much better in that stack. So your downstream user can the data and report they just need.

Name: Opeyemi Fabiyi
Content: And if your downstream stakeholders will need aesthetic reports then maybe you want to integrate Tableau/Power BI, but I doubt you want to integrate multiple BI layer at this stage
dbt*

Name: Opeyemi Fabiyi
Content: Superset is also an family of SQL based viz tool, however it’s similar to Looker & Lightdash because it also help you treat your report and dashboard as a code.

Name: Opeyemi Fabiyi
Content: This feature of treating report and dashboard as a code with version control and all is what others don’t have yet.  So you can explore Superset/Metabase/Lightdash and finalize which one works.

Name: Opeyemi Fabiyi
Content: They are all open source viz tool, so if your goal is to help your organization minimize cost and yet get the best you can go the open source route.

So I can tell you from my experience (and what my model has pointed out to me) that age really might not be a good parameter. From our pilot phase, when we subjected the collected data to modeling, we that the most risky driver was an old man, the 2nd most risky was a young fellow, 3rd was also an old man.. About the same thing played out in the category of safe drivers.

Now coming to practical explanations, for those who have lived in kwara before and knows Unilorin very well, my old man (dad) has on several occasions driven all the way from Ganmo to Unilorin under 15 minutes, which is one of the most dangerous things I think anyone would want to do
I have cousins who are wierd drivers as well
I used to be an ajala traveler before I stopped that earlier this year when the roads were becoming more unsafe

This is why it is a ratio. You’re definitely looking at a large number of people and there’ll definitely be exceptions. Out of 100 old people, less than 30 will be crazy drivers and over 50 young drivers will pose as a high risk on a scale of 1-100
So trying to say younger people drive in risky manners, while the older ones drive in a safe manner might be untrue in all cases (using the Nigerian scenario)
Well you may be right, the pilot phase consists of 89 drivers, but the final model was built on 74 drivers who met the set standards for our modeling
Oh interesting
Probably when we have a larger number, we can get more clarity
For clarity, it’s not just old and young. It’s a range like. 18-25. 26-35. 36-45 etc

So a major concern now is that with our systems, we are able to rank a driver as either being a safe driver, or a risky driver.. How do you think this affects the decision of insurance companies in awarding claims to policy holders?
Then with our anti-loss system, we are also able (to a large extent) to determine the guilty or innocent driver in the case of an accident
How can these be factored into the claims ratio
Or better put, in this first scenario, what's the conventional way of dealing with such issues?

Okay, so those that are known as high risk can be charged excess of loss.. By excess of loss, you’ll pay part of your claims yourself by a particular percentage, say 30%. So, if you have a claim of 100k, you’ll pay 30k and insurance will pay 70k. This will enable you take necessary precautions
I know (read) that insurance companies do carry out researches before they award claims to holders.
Ok
So regarding this, let's say a particular driver has come with claims more than once, does this also affect the amount he will be awarded for subsequent claims?
Yes, his premiums will also increase
Awesome 🥰
So do you think our system will help insurance companies improve their claim ratios, while also protecting the interests of policy holders?
We're routing for UBI such that if as a policy holder, I don't come for a claim this year, then by next year, I should get some discounts in my premium
It's still InsurTech to me. There are a number of them around the world.
@2348108522573 biko check your DM 🙏
Yeah I get, I'm only trying to clarify that the *tech* is what we do at our end, while leave the *Insur* to the insurance companies.. 🤠🤠
Yes, this happens. There’s a name for it. No claim discount or so
No claim bonus
I guess a number of policyholders are not aware of this 🤔
Yes😂 they don’t
Insurance companies cashing out steadily on policyholders ignorance 😂😅
But insurance companies usually reduce the premium rate for these kind of loyal policyholders
One massive claim can clear all the cash outs tho🌚

If you are in Europe, the implication of IC is that you will have to register as a sole proprietor at the local tax office and won't have many employment benefits like Temi said.No insurance and other things that are made compulsory by the local labour law.. You will be seen as an entrepreneur and the company contracting you will be seen as your customer.. You will have to declare the taxes from your business(Your salary in this case) yourself and give the government their share. If you like, japa with it 😅. Also, because the company is not paying insurance and other stuff, your salary will be higher.. But in Nigeria, it is a no man's land. It doesn't matter like that which one you choose. In fact, just go the independent contractor thing if your are in Nigeria.

Name: Opeyemi Fabiyi
Content: @2347038455619. Just as @2348180472075 mentioned Khimball approach majorly leveraged the ETL paradigm prior the Cloud DW where storage and computing resources was a limitation.. Many approach proposed by Khimball still form the fundamental for any Dimensional Modeling, however there is more allowance for stuff as against the strict rules defined by Khimball. Interestingly many still hold on to Khimball, Data Vault and Immnon for that approach.. So the fundamental of Khimball star schema, fact and dimensions still applies only that now we now have options of leveraging OBT (One big Table). The approach to Dimension modeling is now opinionated which is very challenging because you have to decide if you want to adopt Khimball or OBT or an Hybrid and also determine when using Khimball will be much better.. Interestingly there folks that still adhere to Khimball 100%. I recently designed a model for a client discarding Khimball because I felt for that use case it won’t be optimal for downstream users. The client didn’t accept that they want to adhere strictly to Khimball. So lot of decision need to be made as it relate to approach and trade-off.

Thank you boss.. As someone that as worked as an Systems Analyst and Product Owner.. I am quite familiar with Products and Data Teams and handling Stakeholder expectations.

For example, a data product can be a metric (or suite of metrics), a dashboard, a machine learning model, a ML platform, an experimentation platform, etc.. In many cases, these various products are technical products. The job of a data product manager is to strip of all the technical complexities so that a business or other type of non-technical user can use it efficiently.

It's interesting because most manager roles in the data space are more of management than technical leadership, but the data product manager role just hit different.

What makes the role really interesting is that it puts you at the interface of business strategy and technical leadership. Most data product managers I know are strongly business-oriented, yet technically excellent in data. I've been taking a lot of interest in this role lately.

There are only three roles I know in Data. Data Analyst, Data Scientist(where AI or ML or anything engineer) and DE. *All other roles dey disguise one way or the other* 🤣😂

Honestly, the space is still new. So there's a lot of disparity in how organisations handle data products and the associated roles. But typically, a data product manager will be in charge of data team leads, especially if the role is generic. What I mean is that some data product managers are tasked with very generic responsibilities, like handling the entire suite of data products. So imagine if the person is to coordinate everything from metrics to dashboards to machine learning to experimentation. Then you can be sure he or she will be supervising several team leads.. However, some data product manager roles can be very specific. E.g., some just require you to focus on ML platform and strategy. In that case, such a person may be directly leading a team.. Finally, I think there's a difference between a data product owner and data product manager. A data product owner may just own or build out something very specific and be in charge of that. More like the "individual contributor" role that is more common with senior software engineer positions. On the other hand, the data product manager will seat at the intersection of business strategy and technical operations. He will also manage people a lot, not just the product.

Content: Please I'm not really getting this aspect of contributing to open source as a data engineer, and it seems like there are some core fundamentals one need to focus on to get there, most especially cores of software engineering. I said this since ETL is mostly about tools, and open source tool are mostly tending towards an aspect of ETL.

I think one very important thing for the data lead or head of data or CDO is to gain credibility and trust really fast. The how will vary from organisation to organisation based on maturity. For me, it was starting with BI because BI wasn't yet at a mature stage and I chose a use case that was visible to execs but also not to complex to execute. However, if I was leading the data team in a bank or telco, that probably won't fly, a DS use case would have been more ideal or even a DE use case where we simplify infrastructure and speed up time to insights.. I think it is important to scan the landscape before setting up the team and determining the high value low hanging fruits.

I think one also needs to move as fast as possible with a lean team. You can run BI and DS projects in parallel. If there a data issues, you can even add a data management project too. Getting visibility and credibility early is super important.

I read Kolapo’s submission, 💯 spot on, my take and approach is quite similar.. There is usually a business strategy that spells out the must win battles for most/all businesses usually done with an OKR or Strategy Map/Scorecard, as a CDO, it’s best to obtain the business strategy in conjunction with some environment scanning and prepare a data/analytics strategic response to the business strategy. This response is in form of objectives or short-medium-long term plans of the data team that aligns with the business strategy, this may come with a couple of adjustment from the stakeholder.. This gives a CDO an idea of what his/her team should look like in the next 12 months.. From my experience, starting out a new team is usually BI focused especially in corporate/enterprise, might not be same for Startups, this is because there’s an urgent need to deliver tangible/impactful elementary results which a BI team can handle end-to-end. You begin to pitch the need to scale out the team and infrastructure after delivering some tangible results (which I think is similar to Kolapo’s stand on building credibility), this is where you bring in a DE/DS because there’s a need for speed and reduce time to insight.. Prioritisation is the answer to ad-hoc requests, if not well managed, it can become a monster that keeps comings, you study the volume and frequency in a short period, the result will tell if you actually need to also scale up the BI resource in addition to scaling out to DE/DS even though you create time allowance in your initial strategy to give room for handling ad-hoc requests (you have to help save cost)

Very solid thoughts from @2348180472075, @2347069361298, @2347038455619. To add to the interesting discussion, I like to look at the data value stream as a coin with three sides — Infrastructure/DE as one face, BI/DA as the other face, while Data Science (ML, research, experimentation, etc) as the edge.. The infrastructure side is usually more of a long-term, indirect, value-generator for the business. BI/DA is typically the shortest-term value-generator. DS, being the edge, is the highest value-generating side and has the greatest potential for keeping a business ahead in light of competition and market share. We all know not every org needs to have (or can even have) all 3 in place immediately. Some start with BI, others with DE. DS typically comes in at varying levels of data maturity depending on the industry. For example, most large orgs typically focus first on BI just as @2347069361298 pointed out. Non-tech startups also focus primarily on BI, while for tech-heavy startups, the focus is mostly on data infrastructure and then DA/DS.. When setting up a data team, knowing exactly which side(s) to focus on will depend on the org's maturity level and its short-medium-long term goals. This is where a data strategy comes in, to address the org's needs from where it currently is, and also give direction to it's growth trajectory in light of data value generation. For me, a data strategy should be a precursor to setting up a data team. Without data strategy, a data team could be headed for trajedy.. Preparing a data strategy that translates business strategy into tactical technology execution and resultant business outcomes is one of the first things a CDO or Head of Data needs to do, except there's already a data strategy in place. In fact, sometimes, a data strategy changes business strategy and forces the business to adopt new initiatives that can give it the advantage in the market (e.g., what Netflix did by blending a defensive and offensive data strategy). This kind of data strategy optimises the business strategy until it reaches doninance.. For a Head of Data, I think the biggest challenge is in getting buy-in from senior leadership, especially in large orgs. As @2348180472075 pointed out, getting visibility and credibility early is very important. Senior leadership don't care about technology until it communicates value. The challenge is in making data strategy expressive enough that it transcends beyond the technology and workflows to growth opportunities that can meet or exceed business expectations. Technology is tactical, execs will only see strategy when the tech is connected to business outcomes. This is the only way to create trust, and without trust it's hard to get buy-in from senior leadership to support potentially valuable data initiatives.. This leads me back to the data value stream as a coin with 3 sides. As a way to build trust with execs, one key thing a data strategy must be able to communicate is near-term value generation. This is where BI comes in most times. Execs are able to quickly see and quantify business impact. Once trust can quickly be established, the data strategy can then go on to present the value proposition in the other 2 sides. Based on such a strategy, if I'm to build out a data team for a large org at a low data maturity level, the first 6 to 12 months would look something like 60-70% BI/DA, 20% AE/DE and 10-20% DS. Ad-hoc requests can be prioritised under the BI slot.. Once there's a track record of success, and credibility is established, senior leadership then knows they can trust you with value generation with DS and DE that can be more long-term. At this point, the focus can then shift significantly from BI. For tech-focused startups my approach will be different, my prioritisation will be heavier on DS and DE. This is because tech startups are generally already sold in on the huge potential of these 2 sides, not to mention those that focus heavily on data products.

KMeans clustering is an unsupervised learning technique that aims to group “data points” together into groups by calculating “centroids” or center points where other data points that are closer to the centroids are grouped with that centroid

This is an example. We have the whole of Ibadan as a big space (without the houses or anything, just a very very big land) filled with people on different points. Now we want to group the people using properties like “old”, “rich”, “healthy”, and the likes. To actually know these groups, we need to first calculate the positions of the most “old”, most “rich”, and most “healthy” among the people in the space. Calculating this allows us to zero in on the number of groups we want. Afterwards, the distance between each data point and each of the centroids is calculated, and the smallest distance out of the calculated ones is attached to a centroid, and thus belongs to that “cluster”. True.. I learnt this last year. I've always been a stark antagonist of ESRI tools until last year when a client insisted on it.. I had to learn it. And wow, I'm loving the ease that comes with it. So many ready made, plug-and-play tools.. You can easily build your website with WordPress and embed your dashboard and map there.
Beautiful submission

Same thing with cloud platforms. Do you know many people who do data science/eng on cloud are mostly biased towards any of AWS, Azure or GCP?. I started to use Oracle Cloud in 2020 and I was deeply amazed by its vast functionalities and flexibility for data science and DataOps. Most importantly, the data UX is something else. The truth is, just because something isn't popular doesn't mean it can't deliver or even outperform the popular ones. This is why in this data space, you have to constantly update yourself and get familiar with a vast array of tools. Otherwise you get outdated. It is true that we don't need to jump at every new tool, and even if we wanted, where's the time? However, just getting familiar with the various innovations in data science tooling and infrastructure would suffice.

Another thing I learnt is, when you really need a tool, you'll find a way to learn it within a short time. That's as long as you learnt the fundamentals.. Early this year, I applied for a software developer role. The prerequisite was to build a graphql API and consume it with a react front end.. It was the first time I heard of graphql. Yet I was able to complete the challenge within five days.

If I'm to give you an answer because you want one then, number 1 can be predictive approach and number 2 can be causal inference approach. The reason is that number 2 seems to depend on factors about the employees work experience and track records. Therefore we can adopt an improve baye's theorem referred to as Causal Calculus, e.g The probability that employee should gain subsidy because they spent this x-years and the salary is below NGNy. The  EDA will tell if the approach is less costly compare to number 1. But number 1 is more of how the historically employed college graduates have succeeded and also benefits the company, thereby taking a look at predicting the churn rate and the cost of retaining them over the same period as number 2.. In summary, DS problems are not always straight forward but then, a stakeholder who has no idea is requesting for a straight forward answer. A lot about the problem statement is tied to the 'why?'.. This 'why?' comes with 'what? Where? and when?'; which I believe EDA will tell you. The how is the implementation which comes last.. #You_too_talk_own

The answer to this is that they are both causal inference problems. They are both problems that answer yes or no, either of which require evidentiary support because they are decision choices. Machine learning would not suffice to approach those questions, at least not in the way they were posed. The questions were posed as decision questions. The answer must be a single, justified, decision response.. A prediction problem will look something like "Are college graduates better employees (by job performance or other metric)? Then we can go into historical data and use machine learning to capture the relationship between observatory variables and outcomes. Machine learning uses correlation to make predictions. But the model doesn't guarantee there's causation. The original question 1 is not asking if college graduates will be better, it's asking if the decision to hire college graduates is right. It's asking for cause and effect. The response must describe a policy that supports the relationship between the decision (not the variables) and the outcome. The model that will achieve this must infer what the cause-and-effect policy is.. For the rephrased question, machine learning will produce knowledge that asserts the likelihood of your decision quality being high, should you make the decision based on some metric. The likelihood is never a 100%. For the original questions, however, causal inference will produce knowledge that asserts definitively that your decision quality is high, whether it's a yes or no. Machine learning supports decisions, causal inference outputs decisions. To justify a causal inference assertion, the policy must prove to make better decisions than a person making decisions using the best available metrics from machine learning. That's more sophisticated than anything simple correlation can handle because the number of factors that contribute to decision quality is very high.
https

Interesting. No 2 is rightly causal inference. But if you implement Bayesian inference in the way you described it in your example, it would not be causal inference and the results would be off. Working out the probability that an employee should get the subsidy makes it a predictive probabilistic model. It means you are looking at each employee and computing the posterior probability distribution of the outcome, conditioned on the joint distribution of the observations for that employee. That is a predictive approach.. Then, for question 1, check what I noted in my answer about the difference between the question versus when it is slightly rephrased. Question 1 is causal inference because it's a question of whether or not to make the decision. The response is a yes or a no that must be justified as the right decision. Machine learning doesn't justify decisions, it gives a certain likelihood that a decision quality will be high if the decision is taken based on some metric. Subtle differences 😁

Thanks for your input, but I disagree with you because conditional probability is different from causal calculus. The theory is the same but the mathematical application is different because causal calculus is based on actual occurrence of the event, e.g P(x | do{y}) - probability of x given that y is done or carried out successfully; is different from P(x | y) - probability of x given y(irrespective of the condition).. This I have applied on a real life project of recent.. For your follow up, read my sentence above. I said, 'if I'm to give you an answer because you want one' meaning I don't allow stakeholders to rush me. My approach is simple, think of fundamental ways the problem can be solved. Bucket those approach and isolate them then, analyse the available data, and combine the findings before suggesting the best way to the stakeholders. By so doing, you save yourself and the project including the stakeholder. Well I agree that they are both causal inference but try to understand the last part of the question.. #If_ rush_DS_e_go_rush_you
<Media omitted>

@2348137741580, Again, interesting thoughts. Note that my goal in discussions like this is not to stimulate argument but to foster conversations that lead to better understanding of the nuances of subject matter.. I like your emphasis on causal calculus; it's a powerful tool that extends Bayes theory to model the effect of interventions. However, you cannot say conditional probability is different from causal calculus. This is because causal calculus is built on it. The application is also not different; in fact causal calculus applies conditional probabilities.. Secondly, the way you have described P(x | do{y}) makes it, in fact, the same as P(x | y) because the latter updates the degree of belief in x as information about the occurrence of y arises. For example, during inference in probabilistic modelling, we feed in data of actual occurrences to a trained Bayesian belief network or other suitable probabilistic graphical model, and the network returns the probability of the outcome based on those inputs that have actually already occurred.. What you missed is that the difference between P(x | do{y}) and P(x | y) lies in applying external intervention to hold y constant in P(x | do{y}). In P(x | y), the y event can change and each time changes occur, our degree of belief in x gets updated. In P(x | do{y}), we set an intervention to force y not to change and want to see the combined effects of this intervention and the observations on x.. With that being said, causal calculus cannot be applied for the questions in the way you have described it, given the way I specified the questions. Understand that the questions are not asking for inference based on relationship between observations and outcomes from historical data. They are asking for the relationship between a yes-or-no decision and the outcome of that decision. So in this case, it is not P(good performance after subsidising education | years spent & salary upper bound) more like what you earlier specified. It would actually be P(good decision | do{decision}).. On a last note, I agree with you that projects need not be rushed. A data scientist must carefully decompose the problem so well to understand what simple steps to take first before adding complexity if needed. However, I specified the 2 questions the way I did to present a data science use case that even many data scientists are not familiar with. My goal was specifically to stimulate reasoning about how to approach those problems from a decision science perspective. It doesn't mean they cannot be tackled in other, simpler ways. Also, machine learning can solve the 2 problems when you slightly rephrase them to shift from the decision maker to the data treatments the decision is to be made upon.. For us that come from the mathematics field, it's a lot easy to catch these nuances because of years of reasoning grounded in rigour. Communicating it to a broad audience is a skill only a fraction of us have.

You can always switch ...just register with the PFA ur new company uses and give them ur pension pin.. We operate a contributory pension scheme in Nigeria, u contribute from a minute percentage from ur salary, and ur employer thus too
Employers aren't supposed to choose your pension administrator for you.. They're supposed to take who you have and deposit for you.

Theoretically! Yes. But in reality most company have an SLA with some PFA to make pension operation easy, and they might insist you switch.. FYI! My firm as a PFA, they have suggested I switch but I haven't

The problems I posted the other day about causal inference are also behavioural problems. Where a company has to decide whether or not to subsidise college education for its employees.. Here knowledge from data science, behavioural science and decision science are needed to fully specify the complex relationship between the decision and the outcome.. Because as it turns out, there's a complex behavioural dynamics that influences performance on the job. A company has to know whether having educated employees will optimise this behavioural dynamics and ultimately improve job performance. If job performance improves, the decision is high quality. Else, the decision is low quality. With causal inference, we can test several combinations of behavioural dynamics until we fully understand what exact combination is required to maximise the desired outcome. With that full policy, we can then infer whether or not the decision is high quality.

The goal of an analytical approach like this is not to definitively make money in every single scenario, but to quantify what decision is best to take and how much risk that decision exposes you to.. For example, you opt for the second option not because you know for sure you will get ₦1bn in one trial, but because you know the probability of getting it and you know the expected utility.. The goal is not to make money every time, but to take the risks that will bring about the highest cumulative gains when such offers come over and over again.. It will take this trial being repeated 1000 times to get to ₦1bn if we always choose option 1. But for option 2, even if we get ₦1bn twice in 1000 trials (which is almost impossible), you already have twice as much.
It's the concluding paragraph for me.👌🏽 Almost summarizes the whole discussion we have had while it effectively rationalizes any decision that may be taken if presented with varying circumstances.

Name: Opeyemi Fabiyi
Content: Data issue na your mate 🥱
No send VN abeg...your voice is too sweet 😍

We need to understand that it is difficult to present something technical casually to business guys wey no sabi jack. So I would suggest this line of approach below.. Firstly ehn, this is not happening for the first time and since according to them, these 2 or 3 rows affects figures greatly. I would want to say it is some kind of accounting scenario as trust me if the top Stakeholders gets displeased easily with this (which seems more like a toxic workplace to me already)  then, they should have done the following.. 0. Understand why the business is so irritated and angered by this.. 1. On the second occurrence, they should have escalated seriously in such a way that they would let the Business Top Guns know the consequences of having to handle this from the internal team's end and raised SLA concerns because this is third party data. SLA and compliance are very important when dealing with third party data. It is good as Engrs to know what level of accuracy to expect when dealing with external systems so as to put this into design consideration. Read the docs and understand the SLAs of this external tools and systems first.. 2. Dedicate time to investigate and perform analysis to prove it is really that a few missing records that causes a discrepancy. They are non-technical people and they won't try to understand the issue unless you *STORY-TELL IT*. Also come up with recommendation and highlight you really need the vendor's assistance.. 3. And Since the third Party Guys kept giving the same response, they should have revisited their current Data Env Design and let let the business know the extra cost to put checks on validating extra data because this would mean special implementations on logs and monitoring of Source data.(Though this would give room for even some redundant implementations just to make sure data is valid). 3. Propose new solution and cost analysis to the business on what accommodating this discrepancy from the internal team end would look like.. 4. Get the Business Final decision and shoot
But Business Stakeholder wanting to fire entire team is a Red Flag for me.. It probably means they haven't been getting adequate value from their data.
*If they don't clear the business rift between Engrs and the business, then they won't even be able to clear the major technical bug in their data*

Name: Opeyemi Fabiyi
Content: I know there are laws protecting the engineeering professional ( I can remember Engineering Law course that year), but I don’t know if it applies to Data/Software Engineers 😂

Normally when designing systems, there would have been provision for this. The best thing to do is to attack it vigorously when it occurs once so that it never happens again.. At the beginning, you literally can't over design as part of the goal of a DE is Cost Optimization in terms of Infrastructure.. So it is an iteration you would keep improving on.. *Just make sure to attack it with all you have got when it happens once*. Even the big techs suffer data bugs like this once in a while.. PowerBI dashboard connected to Terabytes of data for that matter sef dey get bug for big tech how much more others.

It does actually. Some countries have things in place.. Why do you think in the UK, you can't sack any Engr anyhow. Instead the companies go dey ball you and they would be extra careful and patient with you.
But in our part of the world, you go just wake up see sey you no fit log in again😂🤣

I'm still wondering how a few rows off will lead to the proclaimed disaster. At 10 million rows, you still have a solid 99.99998% at the very least.. But I feel there are lots of behind-the-scenes we are not seeing here, considering that the project is being executed for a client. Perhaps the issue is not that the missing data has a direct negative impact on the project. It could be that the SLA with the client has a clause that specifies a 100% data integrity requirement, a breach of which would incur a certain cost to the business.. It becomes a problem when the engineers are not aware of this clause or don't even have access to the SLA. It's easier to build precautions aforehand when you already know the impact of the slightest failures.

Okay this is the interesting part😄. If 1 subscribe this month, the source system only captures the date of payment i.e January and ignores the other months in the cycle.. and if another payment is made after the cycle, the system only captures the date of payment.. In other words, the source system does not capture the cycle.. Another case in the source system is how it handles Annual payments.. If I pay in January for a whole year, this equals 3 cycles of Jan to April, May to August, Sept to Dec and the source system only captures the dates JAN, MAY and SEPT with the same subscription_id for the period; i.e 3 records with the same subscription_id and dates that only match the start of the subscription.. I however created surrogate key for subscription_id as I believe that each subscription whether annual or one time payments should be unique.. 2. Based on your analogy, if you subscribe in January only one record is created for your with date in January. If your next sub is in Nov, the system only captures one record for that with date in Nov.. Please ask more for further clarification boss

Name: Opeyemi Fabiyi
Content: Next approach after transforming the source data to reflect the above.. Create a Date spine model to reflect one record per customer per product per month. To create this.. Create a utility date dimension for each months from your db start date to current date (use dbt_utils.datespine). Then use that date dimension to create the the monthly/product/customer subscription data. However, it’s a bit tricky with your use case so you will need to factor in month in-between when there was no activity/subscription for a particular customer/product. To help you can create an helper column to identify status change (more like active, church, reactivation ) using the scenario I painted for myself (Jan - April, I’m active, May - September *churn* and October - I reacted my plan for that particular product since your own case have a dynamic of multiple instances)

A lot of us graduates don't  know anything... We only know formulas n know how to solve this n how to solve that..  But the basic concept and driving meaning / Insights from our analysis, that knowledge is far from us.. I had to self-study, asking questions of why and why not. Name: Opeyemi Fabiyi
Content: <Media omitted>
How did you go about automated quality monitoring

*Data Quality Dashboard*. 🌻So, you will define Business Rules.. 🌻 create Data Quality Metrics from the business rules. 🌻Then create thresholds from the Quality Metrics.. Finally, your SQL Engine 😁.. 1. Create table for business domain and data field. 2. Create another table to store data quality rules and metrics with thresholds.. These tables are relational.. This will make your data quality activities programmable as you have parameterised the fields involved. It becomes easier to also scale. You can expand across different domains.. Customer, Products, Agents, etc... The last part is implementation, you can use any programming language here, I only have experience with C# implementation and SQL.. You can write SQL Stored Procedures functions to evaluate each data quality rules picking rules, values, and thresholds dynamically from the tables and store the results in another table which gets plugged to Power BI for visualisation.
Unfortunately, I have carried my bag and followed the LowCode way these days 🤣🤣🤣

I was asking because it’s not exactly best practice to build LookML dashboards or create derived tables in LookML.

Lookml dashboards are never dynamic. You might find a template in their documentation but since dashboards are not monolithic or in the same, consistent format, building a template for one dashboard may not be the best use of time.

Content: Curious what’s the stack like that influence what you want to build?. Looker connected to Big-query? Yeah?

This is my guess. And since PDT is involved, maybe a heavy model that requires regular refresh based on timestamp.

Name: Abraham Musa
Content: Yeah. Bigquery to Looker.

Name: Abraham Musa
Content: Yeah. I'm told there's restriction to the native SQL you create within a single view. Also, for now you can read from BQ to looker but reverse not possible.

Name: Abraham Musa
Content: BTW, does BQ have some form of scheduling for SQL codes?

Name: Abraham Musa
Content: Is that what dbt does?🤔

@2348163815935 you can create derived tables and add the triggers that fit your objective. It could be time triggers. That’s literally what makes a PDT. You can reference the PDT in other views using {example.SQL_TABLE_NAME}

Name: Opeyemi Fabiyi
Content: Do that within Looker using triggers

Name: Abraham Musa
Content: Okay. Thanks both. Any need I should be concerned about the first statement? I wonder how much of a processing capacity looker has backend. 🤔

Naaa. Looker is good. The only think you might worry about is query run time

Name: Abraham Musa
Content: Yeah. Trying to run one colleague dashboard. Was very slow mehn.

Name: Opeyemi Fabiyi
Content: You can use looker to do it. The only challenge will be with build that with PDT which is why it’s best practice as @2348068428052 suggested to push some transformation upstream with a tool like dbt. So Looker only reference a transformed model view

Name: Opeyemi Fabiyi
Content: *build time

That might be worse since you’re creating a PDT. You can make an incremental PDT so it doesn’t rebuild your table every time it runs. It can just add the new fields from BQ. This would reduce query run time. If you have an admin access, you can view your looker usage and query run times and use that view to adjust and optimize accordingly

Name: Abraham Musa
Content: Okay. Super useful details guys. Any thoughts on this?

Name: Opeyemi Fabiyi
Content: That’s why I ask if you’ve written LookML before.. You can check their docs if there’s a template you can leverage on, however it will be dependent on the metrics or what need to be created downstream which will influence how you write your LookML and necessary conditions you enforce.

I usually don’t subscribe to LookML dashboard 😂. But you can also create one dashboard and if you have data leaders in the department of your stakeholders, you can ask them to recreate from the one you’ve created. Nice dashboard. However, one thing you should know about the JHU covid 19 data is that the number of cases and deaths are cumulated continuously on a daily basis per country. (E.g. on the 1st day in the dataset, confirmed cases could be 10, while on the 10th day, the confirmed cases could be 1000. What you should know is that the 10th day value is cumulative of confirmed cases from day 1 through day 10). This explains your very high numbers (E.g. We didnt have 433 mio deaths in the USA). I hope this helps

The reason why the pizza is not treated as a cylinder here is because we can consider the cylinder height as a constant for both pizzas. So we can neglect that height and simply work with the cross-section which is a circle.

I respectfully disagree. If you want to think about it conceptually, try to place two pizzas with 5 inch radius side by side into the cross-section of a single pizza with 10 inch radius. The two pizzas will fit in exactly across the diameter of the larger pizza, but you are going to clearly notice a lot of space between the cross-section of the 2 pizzas and that of the larger one.. What happened? The combined circumference of the 2 pizzas is equal to the circumference of the larger one, but the size is not the same. The size of each pizza is not determined by circumference which is simply the length (or perimeter) of the cross-section. The size is, in fact, determined by area.. So the OP's calculation is valid (of course, approximating the pizza's cross-section as a circle)

I just remembered one technique I used to use back in the day for classification problems. Using scikit-learn's predict_proba to return predicted probabilities. I had no idea it was a dangerously naive approach that only worked well for logistic regression and a few others.. It turns out that when you use it in most other classification tasks, the predicted probability distribution is only approximated and hardly conforms with the expected probability distribution. A better approach is to calibrate the probability distribution using Platt scaling (or for large datasets, isotonic regression). More recently, I discovered another powerful approach with conformal predictions. I'm surprised how these techniques are hardly covered in courses and even the top books in the field.. For machine learning in particular, a really good understanding of the underlying statistical or probabilistic aspects of one's workflow is invaluable. Otherwise, one may not understand why there's a certain results or know what other things can be done to improve them.. Another thing that's very useful in data is communication and collaboration. There are things you can't just figure out on your own.

Name: S+N Ayoade
Content: Always test a tool before taking into production db

Tbh what is most important is how an organisation gets value from data. The MDS tries to simplify that process. The MDS may not be the final promised land but it is better than where we are coming from. The chaos in the data space is a good thing because it points to gaps which still need to be improved upon even in the MDS. At the end of the day the data team must deliver value if the team wants to keep their jobs. So whether MDS o or LDS, or LSA just deliver value. That is the main thing.

One question I am getting asked often by Execs these days is how my projects are either adding to the top line or bottom line. They don't even know the tool stack. I am now having to think through how to track value either from a revenue generation or cost reduction/efficiency perspective. At the end of the day this is what matters. MDS helps to speed up the time to value and in some cases increases value cause it makes some things easier. But you must deliver that value to be relevant one way or the other.
Totally agree 💯💯. Optimised solutions are great but senior execs want to see value, and most times the value-drivers, especially on the near-term, are not the highly optimised solutions.

I must say that ML is an iterative process and there's no one size fits all, so I'd advise you remove the column and check the impact on your model, replace with a constant value and check, basically try everything you can get your hands on and check the impact and go with the one with the least negative or best impact.

Maybe add some automation skill. With these you can function in any hands-on area in data. There are so many aspects of these skills that are highly transferrable. So, even when all sorts of "stack" come up now and then, and the need arises for you to work with new tools, you will find it relatively fast to learn. Many companies even know that having strengths in the above core skills is proof that you can easily transition to new tools.. The long and short is that many skills are ephemeral, but few skills can serve you for the long-term. Focus on the latter.

Okay...noted. I can only say for some of us the knowledge on "the topic of who he is" is limited and quite shallow

Revamps are always necessary.. Had to do one on mine this holidays sef.. Few things that helped me.. 1. Use a blank sheet to chronicle your journey.. a. Career - start from year one. Forget the company, list what tasks you did and what was accomplished in each one.. b. Projects. Use the STAR method.. c. Extracurricular eg. firm contributions. How did you use your interests and skills to help others grow.. 2. Take every item in (1) and slot them under job headings.. For example, I've done work in Audit, accounting, forensic, risk management. And data projects. So I created headings for each one.. 3. Do a search on job titles you're interested in and what skills and tasks are required.. a. Map your discovery to your own experiences.. b. Where are you lagging? Plan to close the gap.. 4. Transfer this to your CV.. a. Summary (may or may not be necessary depending on the years of experience you have).. b. Skills (technical and soft skills related to the role.. c. Experience. d. Portfolio/Projects (include links to git/medium/wherever you documented). e. Education. f. Certifications and trainings. g. Achievement. 5. Items in (4) above can be rearranged to stress what's most relevant to the recruiter.. You want to put the most important thing at the top. People don't always have time to read the world on your resume lol.. If you're going to put a summary section (not objective), make sure you stress leadership ability (if it's a managerial or lead role) and the core areas of your expertise.. There are no hard and fast rules to these things tbh, but cv revamps are an ongoing thing in your career.. Keep a working documents on G-doc to take note of accomplishments and tasks so you don't forget.. ✌🏽

Even though he might be right that there are fewer aspiring data engineers,  those additional points are not it.. People know of its existence, unlike solution architects or analytical engineers, and others in that aspect.. He is very wrong about data scientists avoiding software engineering, at least for those that want to move. Most data scientist role now has a software engineer bit embedded in their job description.  The difference between machine learning engineers and data scientists is almost non-existent. You will solve leetcode problems and algorithm problems at the recruitment stage. After getting the job, you will develop things. It will be difficult to avoid it.

And yes, the "prediction" envelope. A lot of fresh data scientists have that issue too. They believe they are coming to import models from sklearn, fit them to data, predict, and voila! Money flows in.. If you are lucky (unlucky), you might be doing that. I know people who have been doing that well in their careers.. However, you might be creating complicated models and pipelines and architecture that predict (or __ call __) will be a  stage in your problem.

The Nigerian National Petroleum Company (NNPC) Limited has approved an upward review in the pump price of Premium Motor Spirit (PMS) from N165 per litre to N179 per litre, effective today (Tuesday).. NNPC in a notice to fuel marketers directed them to change the petrol price on pumps to the new price effective today. This was even as the company equally increased the ex-depot price from N148.17 to N167 per litre.. This came after weeks of petrol scarcity resurfaced across the country as fuel retailers were adopting different price bands to force unofficial deregulation attempts.. Already, majority of filling stations in Lagos have adopted different price models. While some filling stations have changed the price on their meters to reflect the current price they are selling at, others have left theirs to show the approved retail price of N165 per litre but were selling above the displayed price.. For instance, the Mobil filling station on Agidingbi sold a litre of petrol at N170 per litre on Friday and that was evidently displayed on their meters.. The development was also the same at Enyo filling station at Chisco bus stop, in Lekki, which now sells for N170 per litre, Eterna filling station at Jankade bus stop, Lekki sells at N180 per litre and Mobil Filing station, by Osapa London, Lekki now selling at N170 per litre.

Name: Opeyemi Fabiyi
Content: @2348180472075. Semantic layers is a fraction of Metric layer.. The basic idea of Metric is to solve one major challenge with most BI tool that tracks metrics.. Let’s use Power BI where your semantic layer will be where your build your Data model , define all entities and relationships as well as the DAX measures that will be leveraged for reporting.. The current approach create a bottleneck where any new metrics created with DAX is locked-in in Power BI and can’t be accessible outside Power BI.. As an example, let’s say there is a measure that calculate customers with the highest purchase where there is a measure to do that.. What if Product or Marketing folks need to setup a pipeline that reference that data for further downstream workflow like email marketing or any form of product analytics ? There is a bottleneck to access that at the moment because that metric is locked-in. A Data Scientist can’t access that metric for optimization, they will have to recreate the metric (this create what is called Siloed metrics across). So self service isn’t then self service as proposed which now lead to a new trend called *Headless BI* built on Metrics layer.. What then is this new paradigm?. There is a single source of truth for all metrics that can be accessed across tools and not locked in by any tool. So see it as Decoupling Power BI where the Data modeling and DAX is separated.. Data thought leaders believe this new paradigm will solve a lot of issues.. I hope that help provide more context.
You can chose the *csv* format, copy the output link, then return to PBI, use the *import from web* option

Name: Opeyemi Fabiyi
Content: The issue with the current infrastructure with most BI tool is what is called siloed metrics approach.. Same way we had the issue of siloed data which was solved leveraging 1 single source of truth for Data. Metrics layer is also targeted to provide 1 single source of truth for metrics.

Content: There is currently lot of arguments on the best approach to the metrics layer.. Most are tilting towards SQL since the layer will be consumed by Data Analyst as well as other less tech savvy folks.. Another opinion is pushing for configuration templated YAML approach that will have an API extraction that can be exposed to any tool.. So lot of conversations building up. There are tools already playing in that space though ; Transform, Trace, Gooddata etc.. There is also any option of leverage dbt as the metrics layer. dbt has a feature in the beta stage called *metrics* (I haven’t used it but I’m read the issue in the codebase). Interesting time in the space.. So when folks are shouting semantics layer that’s basically what they are talking about. The rise of Headless BI

One of them is a problem in fluid mechanics. Anyone in engineering or physics should be familiar with Navier-Stokes equations.. With a fairly good knowledge of linear algebra and differential equations, anyone can derive this equation. But... It turns out that there's no mathematical proof of the *uniqueness* and *smoothness* of the solutions to Navier-Stokes, and these 2 properties are necessary for complete understand of fluid behaviour.. Engineers don't believe the proof is needed since the equations work well. Physicists and mathematicians believe the proof is required to understand whether there's a point of limitation of the equation, and if so where?. Till date, some of the finest and greatest mathematicians  have pursued solution of this problem and have made significant progress, but there's still a long way to solving it.

Another problem is the *P versus NP* problem. The time complexity problem many of us are familiar with from computer science.. And beyond what I mentioned earlier about mathematicians way of thinking, there were also some issues with the global math community that Perelman was dissatisfied with.. He published about 3 major papers that led up to the solution of the Poincare conjecture. It took around 3 or 4 years of expert review for his solution to be certified as correct and complete.. But in that period of time, there were other prominent mathematicians (especially from US), who had been racing towards the solution, who tried to discredit him and rubbish his work. Perelman was not a very social mathematician in terms of relating well with other mathematicians, and so most of them treated him like he didn't belong. You know that kind of cult behaviour where people feel someone who isn't in their clique cannot and should not have a seat on the table. It was this kind of behaviour that was the last straw for Perelman.. Imagine trying to run away from so many issues of society and finally you think mathematics is the place where you can hide from all those problems, only to be eventually treated the same way by mathematicians you consider family 🥲. So after solving the Poincare conjecture, Professor Perelman resigned from mathematics work and went back to his village 💀

I'm not a product manager but based on my experience carrying out A/B testing, I'd choose A.

The link between the control (group A) and the treatment (group B) is the homepage. So Option 4 is ruled out.. Option 1 would have been correct based on above context, but the hypothesis is testing specifically for relationship between commercial content volume and clicks, rather than just homepage views. So option 1 is ruled out.. For this to work, both treatment and control groups must specifically view the commercial content, then the proportion of clicks is analysed from those views. This makes Option 5 the correct answer.

I just did a rethink on my last paragraph.. Option 3 should be the correct answer because the hypothesis is checking for proportion of clicks with respect to quantity of commercial content. Not with respect to views on commercial content.. Would like to read others' thoughts as well.
This is convincing as the CTR is a metric that will be used in this experiment.
I'll pick Option 2.. None of the answers are correct.

This is an ad (commercial content) effectiveness experiment.. To likely determine the factor(s) that will lead to fewer clicks through to sponsored pages, you've to establish a baseline in one of the two user groups. If Group A still sees the homepage feed as it is, it means they are the baseline (control group) and won't be exposed to the experiment. Then this leaves you with the users in Group B. It is within this group, you're now able to determine whether there will be a lift or dip in revenue from sponsored content because they're the ones who'll see lesser commercial content (ad). So my answer will be the users in Group B are the ones exposed to the experiment.
